d use of the languages of the respective host communities and also explore related elements of cultural acquisition. A number of aspects of second language acquisition are considered, notably the acquisition of phonology, lexicon and discourse, as well as aspects of sociolinguistic competence. In addition, varying approaches and research methods are reported on, each of which was chosen in consideration of the particular research issue addressed and the particular circumstances under which the research was carried out. These range from psycholinguistic approaches to second language acquisition to variationist approaches, and include both quantitative and qualitative methodologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish languagexVariationzEnglish-speaking countries. 0aLanguage and culturezAustria. 0aLanguage and culturezFrance. 0aLanguage and culturezIreland. 0aPolish peoplezAustriaxSocial life and customs. 0aPolish peoplezFrancexSocial life and customs. 0aPolish peoplezIrelandxSocial life and customs. 0aSecond language acquisitionzAustria 0aSecond language acquisitionzFrance. 0aSecond language acquisitionzIreland. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aPolish diasporic communities.  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  acultural acquisition.  amigrants.  amigration.  apsycholinguistics.  asecond language learning.  asociolinguistic competence.1 aBidzińska, B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDebaene, Ewelina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDebaene, Ewelina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarris, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKopečková, Romana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/